Project Gigapower · 01 — Data Acquisition & Cleaning¶

🌍 Why this notebook matters¶

Project Gigapower is a two‑part engagement for the Strategy Steering Committee:

  1. Notebook 02 – Analysis & Recommendations
    Build the Gigafactory Attractiveness Index, segment countries, and deliver a data‑backed short‑list.

  2. Notebook 01 – this file
    Lay the data foundation that makes those insights credible.

Mission: Fuse five heterogeneous international datasets into **one coherent

country‑year panel (2010 – 2023)** so the analytics team can move straight to modelling without revisiting data hygiene.

🧭 End‑state deliverable¶

  • File produced: model_ready_data.csv
  • Granularity: 80 countries × 14 years × 4 strategic pillars
  • Ready for: PCA, K‑Means, scenario stress‑tests in Notebook 02
  • Data‑quality KPIs: country names standardized (per UN list) with no duplicates, 0.0 % nulls after imputation,

fully typed numeric dtypes.

🔗 Source constellation¶

Pillar Provider Key fields ingested
Market Opportunity World Bank WDI, UN Comtrade GDP, Net FDI inflows, population, EV penetration
Cost Competitiveness ILOSTAT, World Bank WDI Manufacturing wage index, industrial electricity price
Supply Chain Readiness World Bank LPI, BGS Logistics Performance Index, Lithium, nickel, cobalt ore output
Governance & Risk World Bank WGI, ACLED Political risk composite, conflict events

🛠️ ETL playbook executed in this notebook¶

  1. Data Sourcing & Consolidation — Key datasets from sources like the World Bank, ILO, UN Comtrade, BGS, and ACLED were primarily downloaded manually from their websites in trusted CSV files.
  2. Standardized Cleaning — A consistent cleaning process was applied to all incoming data, including mapping various null tokens (e.g., ..) to a standard NaN format for uniform processing in pandas.
  3. Entity harmonisation — To prepare for merging, data was standardized to a consistent country + year granularity. This included aggregating high-frequency source data (like daily conflict events from ACLED) into annual totals per country.
  4. Column-Specific Imputation — A sophisticated, tailored approach was used to handle missing values. Instead of a single method, strategies like forward-fill, linear interpolation, and growth-rate imputation were applied to different columns based on their statistical properties.
  5. Feature Engineering & Master Merge — The cleaned and imputed datasets were merged into a final master file.
  6. Validation suite — A rigorous quality assurance check was performed on the final dataset. This included a final review of data types, a sanity check of descriptive statistics, and a visual inspection of data distributions to confirm that the dataset was 100% complete and ready for modeling.

🔑 Take‑away for the reader¶

This notebook ends with a battle‑tested, analysis‑ready dataset that feeds directly into the scoring, clustering and scenario analysis in 02_Analysis_and_Recommendations.ipynb.
All heavy‑lifting ETL is here; the next notebook can focus 100 % on insight and decision‑making.

UN Comtrade Imports — Aggregation Rationale¶

  • Country-year lens: Our index compares markets annually, so we roll the raw, transaction-level rows (HS code × partner × month) up to a single record per country–year.
  • Partner = World: By keeping only rows where the partner is World (ISO W00) we avoid double-counting bilateral shipments and obtain each reporter’s total import bill.
  • Summing primaryValue: Adding the USD trade values across all products delivers total_imports_usd, a clean proxy for market size and external-demand potential in Pillar 1.
In [7]:
# ============================================================
# Aggregate UN Comtrade imports → country-year totals
#   • file already contains *imports only*
#   • keep rows where partner = World (ISO = W00) to avoid
#     mixing bilateral lines with world aggregate
# ============================================================

print("Aggregating Comtrade import data …")

# 1️⃣  Keep only partner = ‘World’ (ISO code W00)
imports_world = comtrade_df[comtrade_df["partnerISO"] == "W00"].copy()

# 2️⃣  Select the columns we need
cols = ["refYear", "reporterDesc", "primaryValue"]
comtrade_subset = imports_world[cols]

# 3️⃣  Sum trade value by year + reporter
comtrade_agg = (
    comtrade_subset
      .groupby(["refYear", "reporterDesc"], as_index=False)["primaryValue"]
      .sum()
      .rename(columns={
          "refYear"      : "year",
          "reporterDesc" : "country",
          "primaryValue" : "total_imports_usd",
      })
)

# 4️⃣  Fix year dtype → Int64
comtrade_agg["year"] = pd.to_numeric(comtrade_agg["year"], errors="coerce").astype("Int64")

# 5️⃣  Verification
print("✓ Comtrade data aggregated to one row per country-year.")
print(comtrade_agg.head())

Standardize Country Names¶

Creating one canonical list of country names up front lets us standardize every dataset we touch—World Bank, UN Comtrade, ILOSTAT, IEA, USGS, ACLED—so that “United States,” “USA,” and “U.S.” all resolve to the same key; without it, those tiny spelling quirks would torpedo our joins, silently drop rows, and derail the analysis. By mapping or fuzzy-matching each pillar back to this master, we guarantee clean, one-to-one merges, improve overall interoperability, and make our ETL pipeline fully reproducible—no surprises, just data that clicks together.

    print("  •", c)

# 2️⃣  Collect every unmatched label ---------------------------
def report_unmatched(df, col="country"):
    return (
        df[col]
          .dropna()
          .astype(str)
          .str.strip()
          .pipe(set)
          .difference(master_country_set)
    )

unmatched_rows = []
for tag, frame in datasets.items():
    for lbl in report_unmatched(frame):
        unmatched_rows.append(
            {"dataset": tag, "unmatched_label": lbl, "canonical_name": ""}
        )

unmatched_df = (
    pd.DataFrame(unmatched_rows)
      .sort_values(["dataset", "unmatched_label"])
      .reset_index(drop=True)
)

print("=== Unmatched labels (fill in canonical_name) ===")

Country-name harmonization¶

Before we can merge data from different sources, every country label must match the same canonical spelling. This cell applies a manual map that converts the 36 stray names (e.g., “Cayman Isds” → “Cayman Islands”) to our master_country_set, drops non-sovereign aggregates, and checks that zero unmatched values remain—guaranteeing clean, one-to-one joins later on.

# -- add any brand-new canonical names to the master set --
master_country_set.extend(
    sorted({v for v in country_name_map.values() if v is not None}
           - set(master_country_set))
)

def harmonize_country_names(df, col="country", mapping=country_name_map):
    """Replace funky labels with canonical ones and drop aggregates."""
    df = df.copy()
    df[col] = (
        df[col]
          .replace(mapping)
          .astype(str).str.strip()
    )
    df = df[~df[col].isin([None, "None", "nan"])]
    return df

# apply to the pillar-1 frames
wdi_clean    = harmonize_country_names(wdi_clean)
comtrade_agg = harmonize_country_names(comtrade_agg)

# sanity-check
def report_unmatched(df, col="country"):
    return set(df[col]) - set(master_country_set)

print("Remaining unmatched labels:")
for tag, frame in {"wdi_clean": wdi_clean, "comtrade_agg": comtrade_agg}.items():

Merging and Saving Pillar 1 Data¶

This code block will perform three actions:

  1. It will merge wdi_clean and comtrade_agg using an inner join. This is the key step that automatically removes any "Orphan" countries that don't exist in both datasets.
  2. It will verify the merged data.
  3. It will save the result to our first clean data file: Pillar1_Market_Opportunity.csv.

Our first step for this pillar is to download data on mean monthly manufacturing wages from the International Labour Organization's statistical database (ILOSTAT). This will form the basis of our "Cost Competitiveness" score.

The data will be downloaded in local currency units (LCU), and in a later step, we will acquire exchange rate data to convert these values into a standard unit (USD).

Filtering Strategy for the ILOSTAT Dataset¶

The raw dataset downloaded from ILOSTAT is comprehensive but very broad. To prepare it for our analysis, we must perform several filtering steps to isolate only the data that is relevant to our project. The following actions will be taken:

  1. Select the Currency Type

    Our goal is to measure the real-world labor cost for a multinational firm, which operates on market exchange rates. The ILO data is provided in three formats. We will keep only Currency: Local currency. This provides the "ground truth" wage data, which we will convert to USD ourselves using a single, consistent methodology. We will discard the pre-converted U.S. dollars (which uses an unknown "black box" conversion) and the PPP $ data (which is incorrect for measuring business costs).

  2. Isolate the Manufacturing Sector

    Countries report wages under different versions of the International Standard Industrial Classification (ISIC). To maximise coverage while staying strictly within manufacturing, we will keep any label that ends in “Manufacturing” under:

    • ISIC-Rev.2 (code 3. Manufacturing)
    • ISIC-Rev.3.1 (code D. Manufacturing)
    • ISIC-Rev.4 (code C. Manufacturing)
    • the aggregate label “Economic activity (Aggregate): Manufacturing”

This broader filter recovers countries that still publish under older revisions while remaining focused on the same sector.

  1. Standardize the Time Period

    The original download contains data for all available years. We will filter this to keep only the years between 2010 and 2023 (inclusive). This aligns the wage data with the time period established for our other datasets (WDI, Comtrade), ensuring a consistent timeframe for the entire analysis.

Loading and Merging Exchange Rate Data¶

To convert our local currency wages into a common standard (USD), we will now load the World Bank exchange rate data we just downloaded (raw_wdi_exchange_rates.csv).

The process will be as follows:

  1. Load the exchange rate data into a new DataFrame.
  2. Clean and standardize its column names for consistency.
  3. Merge this new exchange rate data with our ilo_clean wage DataFrame, aligning the two datasets by country and year.

This will result in a single DataFrame that contains both the local currency wage and the correct annual exchange rate in the same row, making the final conversion straightforward.

Country-name harmonization¶

Before we can merge data from different sources, every country label must match the same canonical spelling. This cell applies a manual map that converts the 25 stray names to our master_country_set, drops non-sovereign aggregates, and checks that zero unmatched values remain—guaranteeing clean, one-to-one joins later on.

In [21]:
# ==========================================================
# Pillar 2 ─ Harmonise country names in wage & FX datasets
#   • maps every unmatched label
#   • drops metadata rows & true NaNs
# ==========================================================

country_name_map_p2 = {
    # ---------- sovereign states / territories we KEEP ----------
    "Bahamas"                                   : "Bahamas, The",
    "Bolivia (Plurinational State of)"          : "Bolivia",
    "Congo, Democratic Republic of the"         : "Congo, Dem. Rep.",
    "Curaçao"                                   : "Curacao",
    "Côte d'Ivoire"                             : "Cote d'Ivoire",
    "Egypt"                                     : "Egypt, Arab Rep.",
    "Gambia"                                    : "Gambia, The",
    "Hong Kong, China"                          : "Hong Kong SAR, China",
    "Kyrgyzstan"                                : "Kyrgyz Republic",
    "Lao People's Democratic Republic"          : "Lao PDR",
    "Macao, China"                              : "Macao SAR, China",
    "Republic of Korea"                         : "Korea, Rep.",
    "Republic of Moldova"                       : "Moldova",
    "Réunion"                                   : "Reunion",
    "Slovakia"                                  : "Slovak Republic",
    "Tanzania, United Republic of"              : "Tanzania",
    "Türkiye"                                   : "Turkiye",
    "United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland":
                                                "United Kingdom",
    "United States of America"                  : "United States",
    "United States Virgin Islands"              : "Virgin Islands (U.S.)",
    "Occupied Palestinian Territory"            : "West Bank and Gaza",
    "Venezuela (Bolivarian Republic of)"        : "Venezuela, RB",
    "Yemen"                                     : "Yemen, Rep.",
    # already canonical / minor territories (map to self)
    "Cook Islands"                              : "Cook Islands",
    "Guernsey"                                  : "Guernsey",
    "Jersey"                                    : "Jersey",
    "Wallis and Futuna"                         : "Wallis and Futuna",
    "Falkland Islands, Malvinas"                : "Falkland Islands (Malvinas)",
    "Montserrat"                                : "Montserrat",
    # ---------- metadata / aggregates to DROP (→ None) ----------
    "Data from database: World Development Indicators" : None,
    "Last Updated: 06/05/2025"                        : None,
    "nan"                                             : None,
}

# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Ensure all new canonical names are in master_country_set
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
master_country_set.extend(
    sorted({v for v in country_name_map_p2.values() if v not in (None, "None")}
           - set(master_country_set))
)

# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Harmoniser utility
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
def harmonise(df, col="country", mapping=country_name_map_p2):
    df = df.copy()
    df[col] = (
        df[col]
          .astype(str)
          .str.strip()
          .replace(mapping)
    )
    return df[~df[col].isin([None, "None", "nan"])]

# Apply to both frames
ilo_clean           = harmonise(ilo_clean)
exchange_rate_clean = harmonise(exchange_rate_clean)

# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Sanity-check
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
def report_unmatched(frame):
    return set(frame["country"]) - set(master_country_set)

print("Remaining unmatched labels after harmonisation:")
print("  ilo_clean           :", report_unmatched(ilo_clean)           or "✓ none")
print("  exchange_rate_clean :", report_unmatched(exchange_rate_clean) or "✓ none")

Merging, Converting Currency, and Saving Pillar 2¶

This final code block for Pillar 2 will:

  1. Merge the two dataframes using an inner join, which keeps only the countries and years present in both.
  2. Calculate the new wage_usd column by dividing the local currency wage by the exchange rate.
  3. Select the final columns we need.
  4. Save the result to Pillar2_Cost_Competitiveness.csv.
In [22]:
# ==========================================================
# Pillar 2 → dedupe, merge, convert to USD wages
# ==========================================================

print("Resolving duplicates, then merging …")

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# 0.  Deduplicate ILO wages  (mean wage if multiple rows)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
ilo_dedupe = (
    ilo_clean
      .groupby(["country", "year"], as_index=False)["wage_lcu"]
      .mean()                       # or .last() if you prefer
)

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1.  Deduplicate exchange-rate table (keep first)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
exchange_dedupe = (
    exchange_rate_clean
      .drop_duplicates(["country", "year"], keep="first")
      .astype({"exchange_rate_lcu_per_usd": "float"})
)

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# 2.  Inner-join on (country, year)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
pillar2_merged = (
    ilo_dedupe
      .merge(
          exchange_dedupe,
          on=["country", "year"],
          how="inner",
          validate="one_to_one"          # should now pass
      )
)

print(" … merge complete.")

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# 3.  Convert wages to USD
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
pillar2_merged["wage_usd"] = (
    pillar2_merged["wage_lcu"] /
    pillar2_merged["exchange_rate_lcu_per_usd"]
).replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan)

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# 4.  Select final columns
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
pillar2_df = pillar2_merged[["country", "year", "wage_usd"]].copy()

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# 5.  Verify & save
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
print(f"Rows × columns: {pillar2_df.shape[0]:,} × {pillar2_df.shape[1]}")
print(pillar2_df.head())

output_file_p2 = "Pillar2_Cost_Competitiveness.csv"
pillar2_df.to_csv(output_file_p2, index=False)
print(f"Pillar 2 data saved to «{output_file_p2}».")

# ============================================================
# Clean BGS World-Mineral-Statistics  →  `bgs_clean`
# Covers 2010-2022 and keeps **all** minerals present
# ============================================================

print("Cleaning raw BGS data …")

# 1️⃣  Keep only mine-production rows
prod_mask = bgs_df["bgs_statistic_type_trans"].str.lower() == "production"
bgs_work  = bgs_df[prod_mask].copy()

# 2️⃣  Select the essential columns
cols = [
    "country_trans",            # country name
    "year",                     # 2010-01-01 style
    "bgs_commodity_trans",      # mineral label
    "quantity",                 # tonnage
]
bgs_work = bgs_work[cols]

# 3️⃣  Standard column names
bgs_work.rename(
    columns={
        "country_trans"       : "country",
        "bgs_commodity_trans" : "mineral",
        "quantity"            : "production_tonnes",
    },
    inplace=True,
)

# 4️⃣  Fix the year → nullable Int64
bgs_work["year"] = (
    pd.to_datetime(bgs_work["year"], errors="coerce")
      .dt.year
      .astype("Int64")
)

# 5️⃣  Make tonnage numeric, drop rows with NaN tonnage
bgs_work["production_tonnes"] = pd.to_numeric(
    bgs_work["production_tonnes"], errors="coerce"
)
bgs_work.dropna(subset=["production_tonnes"], inplace=True)

# 6️⃣  Restrict to project window 2010-2022
bgs_clean = bgs_work[bgs_work["year"].between(2010, 2022)].copy()

# 7️⃣  Light mineral tidy-up: just lower-case & strip (no filtering)
bgs_clean["mineral"] = bgs_clean["mineral"].str.lower().str.strip()

# 8️⃣  Preview
print("…BGS data cleaned.")
print(f"Rows × cols: {bgs_clean.shape}")
print(bgs_clean.head())
print("\nMinerals present:", bgs_clean["mineral"].unique())

def report_unmatched(df, col="country"):
    labels = (
        df[col]
          .dropna()
          .astype(str)
          .str.strip()
    )
    return set(labels) - set(master_country_set)

# Harmonise BGS country labels to master_country_set

bgs_country_map = {
    "Bosnia & Herzegovina"    : "Bosnia and Herzegovina",
    "Congo, Democratic Republic" : "Congo, Dem. Rep.",
    "Egypt"                   : "Egypt, Arab Rep.",
    "Iran"                    : "Iran, Islamic Rep.",
    "Ivory Coast"             : "Cote d'Ivoire",
    "Korea (Rep. of)"         : "Korea, Rep.",
    "Korea, Dem. P.R. of"     : "Korea, Dem. People's Rep.",
    "Russia"                  : "Russian Federation",
    "Turkey"                  : "Turkiye",
    "USA"                     : "United States",
    "Venezuela"               : "Venezuela, RB",
    "Vietnam"                 : "Viet Nam",
}

# 2️⃣  Verify every mapped target exists in master_country_set
missing_in_master = set(bgs_country_map.values()) - set(master_country_set)
if missing_in_master:
    print("Adding new entries to master_country_set:", missing_in_master)
    master_country_set.extend(sorted(missing_in_master))

# 3️⃣  Apply the mapping
bgs_clean["country"] = (
    bgs_clean["country"]
      .astype(str)
      .str.strip()
      .replace(bgs_country_map)
)

# 4️⃣  Final sanity-check
leftovers = set(bgs_clean["country"]) - set(master_country_set)
print("Remaining unmatched labels:", leftovers if leftovers else "✓ none")

Reshaping the Minerals Data: From "Long" to "Wide"¶

Before we can merge our new BGS minerals data with our other datasets, we need to perform a critical reshaping step.

Currently, our cleaned minerals data (bgs_clean) is in a "long" or "tidy" format. This means a single country-year pair has multiple rows, one for each mineral:

country year mineral production_tonnes
Australia 2022 lithium_minerals 61000.00
Australia 2022 nickel_mine 160000.00

However, our other datasets (like the logistics data) are in a "wide" format, with only one unique row per country-year. To merge them, their structures must match.

The pivot_table function solves this. It transforms our data by taking the unique values from the mineral column and turning them into their own separate columns.

The result will look like this:

country year cobalt_mine graphite lithium_minerals nickel_mine ...
Australia 2022 5900.00 0.00 61000.00 160000.00 ...

This ensures that our minerals data has the same structure as our other datasets, making the final merge straightforward and accurate.

In [32]:
# --- Action: Pivot BGS minerals to wide form ---
print("Pivoting BGS minerals data…")

minerals_pivoted = (
    bgs_clean
      .pivot_table(
          index=["country", "year"],
          columns="mineral",
          values="production_tonnes",
          aggfunc="sum",          # ➊ duplicates summed
      )
      .reset_index()
)

minerals_pivoted.columns.name = None

# ➋ keep Int64 year
minerals_pivoted["year"] = minerals_pivoted["year"].astype("Int64")

# ➌ tidy column names (optional but handy)
minerals_pivoted.rename(
    columns=lambda c: c.lower().replace(" ", "_") if c not in ("country", "year") else c,
    inplace=True,
)

# Fill missing production with zeros
minerals_pivoted = minerals_pivoted.fillna(0)

print("…pivot complete.")
print(minerals_pivoted.head())
print(f"Shape: {minerals_pivoted.shape}")

Loading and Combining ACLED Data¶

To create a comprehensive measure of on-the-ground instability, we will now process the two separate aggregated datasets we downloaded from ACLED.

Our strategy is to combine these two files to capture a broader spectrum of risk:

  • Political Violence Events: This file (raw_acled_political_violence.xlsx) provides the annual count of events like battles and violence against civilians.
  • Demonstration Events: This file (raw_acled_demonstrations.xlsx) provides the annual count of protests and riots.

By merging these, our analysis will account for both organized conflict and popular unrest, giving us a more nuanced risk indicator. Our process will be to load each file individually, clean them, and then combine them to create a single total_disorder_events score for each country-year.

Finalizing Pillar 4: Merging Governance and Conflict Data¶

  • This final step for Pillar 4 constructs our comprehensive risk dataset by merging the long-term governance indicators from the World Bank with the high-frequency event data from ACLED.

  • The process you've designed involves several key actions to ensure data quality and integrity:

    • Pre-Merge Cleaning: A quick data hygiene step is performed on all three source dataframes (violence_clean, demos_clean, governance_clean) to standardize data types and remove any accidental duplicate rows. This is a crucial safeguard to ensure a clean, reliable merge.

    • Create a Unified ACLED Score: The two ACLED datasets are combined using an outer join. A robust method is then used to calculate the total_disorder_events while carefully preserving NaN (missing) values for any country-year where ACLED provides no data coverage. This correctly distinguishes between a year with a true zero events and a year with no data available.

    • Final Left Join: The aggregated ACLED score is then merged onto our main governance_clean dataset. This left join ensures all countries from our governance dataset are kept. The NaN values for ACLED's "no-coverage" years are correctly maintained in the final merged table.

  • The result is a single, clean file, Pillar4_Governance_Risk.csv, that contains the most accurate possible representation of risk, ready for the final stage of our data preparation.

In [51]:
# ==============================================================
# Pillar 4 – Merge governance metrics + ACLED risk
# ==============================================================

print("Beginning final merge for Pillar 4 …")

# ── STEP 0 ▸ keep only project window 2010-2023 ──────────────────
print("\nFiltering ACLED tables to 2010-2023 …")
violence_clean = violence_clean[violence_clean["year"].between(2010, 2023)].copy()
demos_clean    = demos_clean[demos_clean["year"].between(2010, 2023)].copy()
print("✓ ACLED data filtered.")

# ── STEP 1 ▸ harmonise dtypes + de-dupe on all three frames ──────
for tag, df in {
    "violence_clean"   : violence_clean,
    "demos_clean"      : demos_clean,
    "governance_clean" : governance_clean,
}.items():
    df["year"] = pd.to_numeric(df["year"], errors="coerce").astype("Int64")
    dup = df.duplicated(["country", "year"]).sum()
    if dup:
        df.drop_duplicates(["country", "year"], keep="last", inplace=True)
        print(f"  • {tag}: removed {dup} duplicate rows")

# ── STEP 2 ▸ outer-merge violence + demonstrations ───────────────
acled_merged = violence_clean.merge(
    demos_clean,
    on=["country", "year"],
    how="outer"
)

# Flag rows where ACLED has **no coverage at all**
no_acled = acled_merged[["political_violence_events",
                         "demonstration_events"]].isna().all(axis=1)

# Aggregate (treat NaN as 0 **only** for the sum)
acled_merged["total_disorder_events"] = (
    acled_merged[["political_violence_events",
                  "demonstration_events"]].fillna(0).sum(axis=1)
)

# Restore NaN where ACLED contained no data
acled_merged.loc[no_acled, "total_disorder_events"] = pd.NA

acled_final = acled_merged[["country", "year", "total_disorder_events"]]
print("✓ ACLED tables merged and aggregated; NaNs kept for uncovered years.")

# ── STEP 3 ▸ left-merge onto governance indicators ───────────────
pillar4_df = governance_clean.merge(
    acled_final,
    on=["country", "year"],
    how="left"
)

# ── STEP 3a ▸ cast disorder events to nullable integer & duplicate check ──
pillar4_df["total_disorder_events"] = (
    pillar4_df["total_disorder_events"].astype("Int64")   # keeps NaNs
)

assert pillar4_df.duplicated(["country", "year"]).sum() == 0, \
    "Duplicate (country, year) pairs detected in Pillar 4 dataframe!"

print("✓ Final merge with governance data complete (no duplicates).")

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# STEP 4 ▸ save & preview
# --------------------------------------------------------------
output_file_p4 = "Pillar4_Governance_Risk.csv"
pillar4_df.to_csv(output_file_p4, index=False)

print(f"\nPillar 4 data saved → «{output_file_p4}»")
print("\nAfghanistan sample (first 10 rows, all variables):")
print(
    pillar4_df.query("country == 'Afghanistan'")
              .head(10)
              .reset_index(drop=True)
)

Final Master Merge¶

Here, we will combine our four clean pillar datasets into a single, analysis-ready master dataset. We will use a series of inner merges to ensure that every country in our final dataset has a complete set of data across all four pillars.

In [53]:
# =============================================================
# Final Step ▸ Build the Master Analytical Dataset (inner-join)
# =============================================================

import pandas as pd

print("⏳  Performing the final master merge …")

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# 0️⃣    Helper – harmonise dtypes & drop accidental duplicates
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
def prep(df, name):
    df = df.copy()
    df["country"] = df["country"].astype(str).str.strip()
    df["year"]    = pd.to_numeric(df["year"], errors="coerce").astype("Int64")

    dup = df.duplicated(["country", "year"]).sum()
    if dup:
        df.drop_duplicates(["country", "year"], keep="last", inplace=True)
        print(f"   • {name}: removed {dup} duplicate rows")
    return df

pillars_prepped = {k: prep(df, k) for k, df in pillars.items()}

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1️⃣    Chained inner merges (keeps only full-coverage country-years)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
master_df = pillars_prepped["P1"].copy()
for tag in ("P2", "P3", "P4"):
    master_df = master_df.merge(
        pillars_prepped[tag],
        on=["country", "year"],
        how="inner",
        validate="one_to_one",   # raise if merge keys aren’t unique
    )

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# 2️⃣    Final housekeeping & save
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
master_df.sort_values(["country", "year"], inplace=True, ignore_index=True)

print("✅  Master merge complete.")
print(f"   Rows × cols: {master_df.shape[0]:,} × {master_df.shape[1]}")
print(f"   Unique countries: {master_df['country'].nunique()}")

output_file_master = "master_analytical_dataset.csv"
master_df.to_csv(output_file_master, index=False)
print(f"\n📁  Final master dataset saved → «{output_file_master}»")

# Quick peek
display(master_df.head())

Step 3: Final Imputation — A Column-Specific Strategy¶

  • This is the final transformation for our dataset. Instead of applying a single blanket rule to all columns, we will use a more sophisticated, column-specific strategy to handle the remaining missing values (NaNs). This is because different indicators behave in different ways, and a tailored approach yields a more accurate and defensible final dataset.
  • Our imputation logic is broken down by variable type:
    • Structural & Governance Scores (e.g., political_stability_est): These values change slowly over time. We will use a forward-fill then backward-fill method for each country to fill gaps using the last known valid observation.
    • Gradual Socio-Economic Ratios (e.g., lpi_score): For indicators that trend smoothly, we will use linear interpolation to fill small gaps, as it provides a more realistic estimate than simply carrying a static value forward.
    • Economic "Level" Indicators (e.g., gdp_usd, population): For variables that grow exponentially, we use a more advanced growth-rate imputation. We calculate the year-over-year growth rate, fill any gaps in that rate, and then rebuild the series. This correctly preserves the compounding nature of economic growth.
    • Volatile Rates & Event Counts (e.g., inflation_pct, total_disorder_events): For highly volatile data or for columns where NaN has a specific meaning (like "no ACLED coverage"), we will not impute any values for now. We will handle them separately after inspecting which countries we are missing the data for.
  • This tailored approach ensures our final dataset is of the highest possible quality and integrity, ready for analysis.

# =============================================================
# Impute the remaining NaNs  ▸ “all-in-one” cell
#   • builds the schema *once* with every column we need
#   • applies the chosen method country-by-country
#   • finishes with one last safety interpolation
# =============================================================

# 1️⃣  Build the imputation schema  ────────────────────────────
impute_schema = {

    # forward-fill then backward-fill (good for slowly-moving governance scores)
    "ffill_bfill": [
        "political_stability_est",
        "rule_of_law_est",
        "control_of_corruption_est",
        "wage_usd",                          # <-- now included
    ],

    # linear interpolation ±3 years, then ffill/bfill
    "linear": [
        "lpi_score",
        "access_to_electricity_pct",
        "manufacturing_pct_gdp",
        "electric_power_consumption_kwh_pc",
        "gross_capital_formation_pct_gdp",
        "industry_pct_gdp",
    ],

    # multiplicative growth-rate fill (carry forward %Δ)
    "growth": [
        "gdp_usd",
        "population",
        "total_imports_usd",
    ],

    # leave NaNs as-is (true “missing” or 0-/inapplicable)
    "none": [
        "total_disorder_events",
        "inflation_pct",
        "gdp_growth_pct",
    ],

    # mining & ore series — just carry the last observation forward
    "ffill_only": [
        c for c in master_df_filtered.columns
        if c.endswith("_mine") or c.endswith("_ore")
    ],
}

# 2️⃣  Helper used by .transform()  ────────────────────────────
def impute_group(s, method):
    if method == "ffill_bfill":
        return s.ffill().bfill()

    if method == "linear":
        return s.interpolate(limit=3).ffill().bfill()

    if method == "growth":
        lvl = s
        pct = lvl.pct_change().ffill().bfill(limit=2)
        rebuilt = [lvl.iloc[0]]
        for r in pct.iloc[1:]:
            rebuilt.append(rebuilt[-1] * (1 + r))
        return pd.Series(rebuilt, index=lvl.index)

    if method == "ffill_only":
        return s.ffill()

    return s  # 'none' → untouched

# 3️⃣  Run the imputation  ────────────────────────────────────
master_imputed = master_df_filtered.copy()

for method, cols in impute_schema.items():
    for col in cols:
        if col not in master_imputed.columns:
            print(f"⚠️  Column '{col}' not found – skipping")
            continue
        master_imputed[col] = (
            master_imputed
              .groupby("country")[col]
              .transform(lambda g: impute_group(g, method))
        )

# 4️⃣  Final safety net for lpi_score (rare edge cases) ───────
master_imputed["lpi_score"] = (
    master_imputed
      .groupby("country")["lpi_score"]
      .transform(lambda s: s.interpolate(limit_direction="both"))
)

# 5️⃣  Quick audit  ───────────────────────────────────────────
print("\n✅  Imputation finished. Remaining NaNs per column:")
print(master_imputed.isna().sum().sort_values(ascending=False).head(10))

Diagnostic: Pinpointing Missing Data by Country¶

This will confirm that the issue is isolated to a handful of specific countries with sparse data reporting, rather than a widespread problem.

Step 5: Handling Final Missing Values¶

  • Our diagnostic investigation reveals that the few remaining NaNs are not random errors but are concentrated in a handful of specific countries where data is historically sparse or, in the case of Argentina, notoriously volatile.

  • Decision:

    • For the countries with missing foundational scores (lpi_score, manufacturing_pct_gdp, etc.), we will remove them to ensure the integrity of our core analysis. These are not major EV markets, so their exclusion is acceptable.
    • For Argentina, the missing inflation_pct is due to extreme economic conditions. Including it with a NaN value is the most honest approach, but for building predictive models where inflation is a key feature, it's safer to exclude it.

  • Action: We will create a final, clean dataset by dropping all remaining rows that contain any NaN values. This ensures our dataset is 100% complete and ready for modeling.

missing_disorder_df = model_ready_df[model_ready_df['total_disorder_events'].isna()]

# 2️⃣  Get the unique list of countries from that filtered data
countries_missing_acled_data = sorted(missing_disorder_df['country'].unique().tolist())

# 3️⃣  Print a clean report
total_countries_in_set = model_ready_df['country'].nunique()
print(f"Found {len(countries_missing_acled_data)} out of {total_countries_in_set} countries with missing ACLED conflict data:\n")

# Print the list in a readable format
for country in countries_missing_acled_data:
    print(f"  • {country}")

Final Data Treatment: Engineering the ACLED Conflict Feature¶

  • Our diagnostic check revealed a critical insight: the NaN values in the total_disorder_events column are not random. They are overwhelmingly concentrated in stable, developed nations.

  • This pattern is explained by the data source's methodology. ACLED didn’t systematically code most stable OECD countries until their global expansion around 2017. For years prior to this, a NaN for a country like Germany or Japan does not mean "unknown conflict"—it means "no coverage," which serves as a strong proxy for stability.

  • Given this, we will use a sophisticated feature engineering approach instead of dropping valuable data. This provides the best of both worlds:

    • 1. Create a Flag: We will first generate a new boolean column, acled_covered. This flag is True if the original data was present and False if it was missing, permanently preserving the data's origin.

    • 2. Impute with Zero: We will then fill the remaining NaN values in total_disorder_events with 0.

  • This strategy yields a 100% complete dataset ready for modeling. By creating two distinct but related features (total_disorder_events and acled_covered), we give our future model maximum information and nuance to learn from.

In [62]:
# =============================================================
# Final ACLED treatment ─ flag coverage, zero-fill the rest
# =============================================================

# 1️⃣  Boolean flag: did ACLED actually cover this country-year?
model_ready_df["acled_covered"] = model_ready_df["total_disorder_events"].notna()

# 2️⃣  Replace the remaining NaNs with 0
#     (keeps dtype nullable Int64 so NaNs could be restored if ever needed)
model_ready_df["total_disorder_events"] = (
    model_ready_df["total_disorder_events"]
      .fillna(0)
      .astype("Int64")
)

# 3️⃣  Quick sanity check
print("✅  ACLED post-processing complete")
print("   • NaNs left in total_disorder_events:",
      model_ready_df["total_disorder_events"].isna().sum())

# Show the first few rows for a visual spot-check
display(
    model_ready_df[["country", "year",
                    "total_disorder_events", "acled_covered"]]
      .head(10)
)
